In programming, the keyword `static` is used to modify variables, methods, and classes. Its meaning depends on the context in which it is used.

**1. Static Variables:**

When used with variables, `static` means that the variable is shared by all instances of a class. It is initialized only once, when the class is loaded into memory, and its value is preserved between method calls.

```java
public class MyClass {
    public static int myVariable = 10;
}

MyClass obj1 = new MyClass();
MyClass obj2 = new MyClass();

System.out.println(obj1.myVariable); // prints 10
System.out.println(obj2.myVariable); // prints 10
```

**2. Static Methods:**

When used with methods, `static` means that the method can be called without creating an instance of the class. It belongs to the class itself, not to any instance of the class.

```java
public class MyClass {
    public static void myMethod() {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}

